{"commentv2": 1, "number": 32, "id": 1555288, "nreplies": 0, "sticky": 0, "user": "Iroared", "body": "To reiterate some things, specifically for 10-man version (heroic).\n\nPhase 1 - the only noticeable difference is the debuff from detonating a trap; we usually had 2 traps left over. One was usually detonated somewhere in phase 2, and the other before phase 4.\nTransition - sons of flame spawn very differently from normal. They spawn very randomly, e.g. you can get a hammer on the left and 5 elementals next to it, or sometimes only one elemental would spawn near the hammer. The goal is to be quick on distributing people between the sides. The sons themselves only have slightly higher health than in normal mode - around 200k.\n\nPhase 2 - engulfing flames are replaced by world in flames, which casts a shorter version of engulfing flames several times in a row. As soon as the animation for the new flames starts, you can move to the space that was previously covered in flames. Its very easy to move out of, even if you didn't stand at the edge. The ticks don't one-shot you, but they hurt healer's mana, which is very important here.\nAdds from seeds have increased damage when they are close together. We ended up dealing with it just by spreading out slightly once they come out - we could still AoE them and they don't hurt that much.\nTransition - same as the previous one, with added Lava Scions, which tanks have to remember to pick up, hit a couple times, and ignore until the sons are dealt with. Leave one son with low health until the scions are dead or until ragnaros re-emerges, at which point the son has to be quickly killed or it will explode. You really don't want scions alive when the next phase starts, as DPS is very important here.\n\nPhase 3 - the only difference from normal is world in flames, same as phase 2. DPS here is really important, this is the place to use bloodlust/heroism (we actually had our hunter spec BM for this fight, since we don't have a shaman and the mage wasn't able to play for some time). The goal is to get him to 10% before the second meteor, which was really tough timing for us (the first meteor should spawn at about 20% in a successful pull). We always kept trying when the second meteor spawned, but we never got far into phase 4 this way.\n\nPhase 4 - the most important part is getting the meteor(s) out of the way. This is when most defensive cooldowns will be used. The raid has to be precise at positioning within breadths (note: in 4.3 the geysers were removed and you can just stack together). We didn't bother with making people run out to kite meteors, usually knocking it back on cooldown was enough to keep it away until the second breadth spawns.\nOnce the meteor is down, it should stabilize as you don't have to be in a hurry anymore and people can stay around in the old breadth until the way is clear. The main challenge at this point (other than not being overrun by dreadflames) is for tanks to quickly react to roots spawns. The roots will often spawn right next to ragnaros, and he has to be moved away until Empowered Sulfuras (which happens in 8 seconds, unless he stops to cast more dreadflames). If this is not done, the roots will be wasted and you will have to taunt-kite the boss for 10 seconds, which means a lot of wasted tank cooldowns for surviving superheated and additional stress. A good strategy is for the tank not currently on the boss to move out a few seconds before the roots spawn, ready to taunt the boss if he needs to be moved quickly. Once roots spawned and the boss is away from them, the other tank runs behind the roots and gets ready to taunt. The first tank has to remember to stop attacking.\nDreadflames in 10-man is only handled by one person with cloudburst, in our case it was a balance druid who spent most of phase 4 in cat form for faster movement.\nThis phase is very prone to randomness, e.g. first dreadflames spawning near cloudburst can allow the extinguisher to get rid of them completely, whereas if they spawn far away they can quickly get out of control. If breadths spawn in the middle of dreadflames, you're out of luck, you will have to wait for the next one and hope its close by. On our first kill we had very lucky spawns, with 3 breadths spawning in almost the same place.", "date": "2011-10-27T16:19:01-05:00", "rating": 12, "indent": 0, "roles": 0, "deleted": 0, "outofdate": 0, "userRating": 0, "replies": [], "dataTree": 1, "markupDisabledEnvironments": {"ptr": true, "beta": false}, "lastEdit": ["2011-12-24T03:20:27-06:00", 2, "Iroared"]}
{"commentv2": 1, "number": 33, "id": 1560298, "nreplies": 1, "sticky": 0, "user": "SDimou", "body": "I have a really important question to ask about the [npc=53189] adds in 2nd phase.\r\n\r\nI know for sure that they are immune to Taunt but when they spawn, do they fixate on a person until they are dead or is there a way to aggro them (e.g. if you do enough damage on them they turn to you)?\r\n\r\nPlease help :)", "date": "2011-11-02T02:20:31-05:00", "rating": 2, "indent": 0, "roles": 0, "deleted": 0, "outofdate": 0, "userRating": 0, "replies": [{"body": "Molten elementals open with 1M threat on whatever player their seed was cast at.  Threat dropping mechanics such as invisibility, mirror images, fade etc, work to cause them to drop threat from you and go towards someone else who is generating threat on them. This is inadvisable on heroic depending on your raid strat as elementals may target people who were standing out or dropped threat themselves so they could AOE.", "creationdate": "2011-11-08T16:16:56-06:00", "id": 276513, "rating": 4, "commentid": 1560298, "dataTree": 1, "roles": 0, "username": "citrique", "markupDisabledEnvironments": {"ptr": true, "beta": false}, "downvotedByUser": false, "reportedByUser": false, "votedByUser": false}], "dataTree": 1, "markupDisabledEnvironments": {"ptr": true, "beta": false}}
{"commentv2": 1, "number": 34, "id": 1563539, "nreplies": 1, "sticky": 0, "user": "artyfarty", "body": "[b]Rogue facts[/b]\n\n[ul]\n[li]Rogues can kick meteors using [url=http://www.wowhead.com/spell=73981]Redirect.[/url] Yes, Redirect itself will knock back the meteor. No need to throw anything at it.[/li]\n[li]Killing Spree is not as dangerous here as one might think.[/li]\n[li][url=http://www.wowhead.com/spell=1966]Feint[/url] works on all AOE mechanics.[/li]\n[li]Yes, he parrys a lot.[/li]\n[li]It's very easy to vanish and massrez here.[/li]\n[/ul]\n\n[i]edit: fixed \"rouge\"[/i]", "date": "2011-11-05T08:12:46-05:00", "rating": 18, "indent": 0, "roles": 0, "deleted": 0, "outofdate": 0, "userRating": 0, "replies": [{"body": "Maybe because you misspelled [i]Rogue[/i].", "creationdate": "2011-11-13T14:56:00-06:00", "id": 277531, "rating": 3, "commentid": 1563539, "dataTree": 1, "roles": 0, "username": "489166", "markupDisabledEnvironments": {"ptr": true, "beta": false}, "downvotedByUser": false, "reportedByUser": false, "votedByUser": false}], "dataTree": 1, "markupDisabledEnvironments": {"ptr": true, "beta": false}, "lastEdit": ["2011-11-14T15:55:50-06:00", 2, "artyfarty"]}
{"commentv2": 1, "number": 35, "id": 1569675, "nreplies": 2, "sticky": 0, "user": "OldWolf", "body": "I have only ever seen Sons of Flame configurations 2-6, 4-4, or 6-2.  However some strat posts talk about a 3-5 or 5-3 split scenario. Can someone clarify?", "date": "2011-11-11T14:48:21-06:00", "rating": -4, "indent": 0, "roles": 0, "deleted": 0, "outofdate": 0, "userRating": 0, "replies": [{"body": "On heroic the splits can have any number of adds on either side. I have personally seen 0-8, 1-7, 2-6, 3-5, 4-4.", "creationdate": "2011-11-11T17:38:39-06:00", "id": 277162, "rating": 1, "commentid": 1569675, "dataTree": 1, "roles": 0, "username": "citrique", "markupDisabledEnvironments": {"ptr": true, "beta": false}, "downvotedByUser": false, "reportedByUser": false, "votedByUser": false}, {"body": "At about [url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z8KCdlE6m-E]5:50 in this video of the encounter[/url], you have the normal mode splits you might be faced with, all depending on where he lands his Sulfuras Smash.  Heroic mode, afaik (and as Citrique is saying with the splits listed in his/her post above), the spawnpositions are completely random, meaning you can have them all clustered up or widely spread out. RNG ftw, I guess :)", "creationdate": "2011-11-16T08:50:50-06:00", "id": 278088, "rating": 0, "commentid": 1569675, "dataTree": 1, "roles": 0, "username": "Euphemia", "markupDisabledEnvironments": {"ptr": true, "beta": false}, "downvotedByUser": false, "reportedByUser": false, "votedByUser": false}], "dataTree": 1, "markupDisabledEnvironments": {"ptr": true, "beta": false}}
{"commentv2": 1, "number": 36, "id": 1573053, "nreplies": 0, "sticky": 0, "user": "GreenStorm", "body": "As for arcane mages in transitions since they don't have stuns they have to nuke one add as fast as possible I use this tac:\n\n 1) Pop up [spell=82731] before the mob spawns.\n 2) Have [spell=12043] on.\n 3) [spell=30451] it twice\n 4) You can finish it off with [spell=44425] or nuke another near mob with [spell=30451] before clearing its stack.\n\nAnd [spell=12042] is always helpful.\n\n----------------\n\nPhase one: you can always slow fall then blink down.", "date": "2011-11-15T18:08:58-06:00", "rating": -6, "indent": 0, "roles": 0, "deleted": 0, "outofdate": 0, "userRating": 0, "replies": [], "dataTree": 1, "markupDisabledEnvironments": {"ptr": true, "beta": false}, "lastEdit": ["2011-11-15T18:09:25-06:00", 1, "GreenStorm"]}
{"commentv2": 1, "number": 37, "id": 1577563, "nreplies": 0, "sticky": 0, "user": "Namnalia", "body": "Some tips we wiped 97 times for before finally getting our kill yesterday on the heroic ragnaros(10m):\n\nGeneral: Don't waste your time with bad setups. We benched our resto shaman and dps warrior from the very beginning and had our feral dd respec to balance. It may be possible to beat the encounter with unusual setups, but given the time needed to learn it even with a nearly optimal setup (we had Pala/Warrior Tank, Pala/Druid Heal, 2 Moonkins, 1 Demo Warlock, 1 Arcane Mage, Hunter and Rogue), I would never even try it if I had any choice.\n\nPhase 1: If your DPS is decent (and it has to be, otherwise you won't manage P3) slow down on dpsing so that you can detonate a trap at  71/72 percent. This way you'll only have one trap in P1,5/P2 which just eases stuff. \n\nPhase 2: We optimized our complete setup for this phase, taking 2 Owlkins with us and only one melee. Our tactic was going together from one side to the other, spawning all of the adds in one point. Our warlock (me) and our arcane mage, however, started on the opposing side. This way, we could actually help bombing (you always have aggro of the add you spawned yourself) while the melee finished one of our adds, leaving one harmless add for the cleanup. This tactic changed P2 from nearly unmanageable to easy.\n\nBefore P2.5 starts, bring the boss to 42%, wait for World in Flames, then dps him down as hard as you can without using crucial CDs (you'll need them in P3). This way, you can start P3 with 37% instead of 39%.\n\nPhase 2.5: Have one designated DD prepare an add for a later kill, we had a person to do this on both sides and they communicated who would prepare an add according to the hammer position and number of adds. This way, you can optimize the dps on the adds. With good spawn points, we occasionally started P3 without Scions.\n\nPhase 3: we had our hunter and healers take care of the meteors as much as possible to free up the dps, but I guess the main key to success is a good Phase 2.5 and the World-in-Flames-Trick at the end of P2.\n\nPhase 4: Rule number one is definitely: Don't panic. The phase is rather easy now that you don't have to deal with 3+ meteors. We had one range DD (an owlkin) on meteor duty, meaning that he would kick it away again and again and announce the moment we kite it into our zone (usually parallely to the first roots). Afterwards, it's basically tank and spank with a twist, just be communicative about dreadflame spawnpoints. Right before roots spawned, our offtank left the camp to taunt the boss away from roots spawning right under him (happens more often than you would think, especially on good tries). We had some tries where the dreadflames seemed rather unmanagable (spawning as far apart of each other as possible everytime), but in most of the cases, if your fire extinguisher knows what he's doing, he'll manage it. Took us roughly 25-30 tries in P4 to actually get a kill, probably less than 10% of what guilds had to invest before the nerf :-)\n\nPro tip:\nWhen we reached P4 rather consistently, we allowed trash talking during P1 and P2 (not during Submission Phases) to overcome the extreme boredom of the first 8 minutes of the fight until you finally reach the \"hot\" phase. This made the whole progression a lot funnier without causing any unneccessary wipes.", "date": "2011-11-21T09:49:52-06:00", "rating": 3, "indent": 0, "roles": 0, "deleted": 0, "outofdate": 0, "userRating": 0, "replies": [], "dataTree": 1, "markupDisabledEnvironments": {"ptr": true, "beta": false}, "lastEdit": ["2011-11-21T09:53:11-06:00", 3, "Namnalia"]}
